    "reasoning": "First, compute m: n=2000, p=23, so floor(2000/23)=86, and m = 86 - 36 = 50. S contains integers from -100 to 100 inclusive, so |S|=201. We choose a random 50-element subset T of S. For each possible absolute value, define indicators: I_0 for 0 being in T, and for k=1 to 100, I_k for at least one of k or -k being in T. The number of distinct absolute values is I_0 + sum_{k=1}^{100} I_k. By linearity of expectation, the expected number is E[I_0] + sum_{k=1}^{100} E[I_k]. E[I_0] = probability 0 is in T = C(200,49)/C(201,50) = 50/201. For k>0, E[I_k] = 1 - probability neither k nor -k is in T = 1 - C(199,50)/C(201,50) = 1 - (151*150)/(201*200) = 1 - 151/268 = 117/268. Sum: 50/201 + 100*(117/268) = 50/201 + 11700/268 = simplify to common denominator: 50/201 = 200/804, 117/268 = 351/804, so 100*(117/268)=35100/804, total = 35300/804 = 8825/201 after simplification.",
